{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dc1f4062-de17-4e7e-9dad-17160be1dd74","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on Kubernetes:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Getting the file off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives a live view of CPU %, GC, thread pool, etc. — useful before committing to a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails due to network restrictions, you can copy the tool into the container via `kubectl cp` or bake it into your container image.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"794ee7e2-e9f9-4fbf-b6f0-39c6e493fc97","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes. This is a troubleshooting/knowledge question, not a code change request. I can answer this directly from my knowledge.","outputTokens":407,"requestId":"75C2:3766FA:D20D99:F6101D:69FE8C60"},"id":"c19fe2f6-0c31-4285-baf6-c9143b7263a0","timestamp":"2026-05-09T01:22:50.323Z","parentId":"e439e9d8-746d-4a5a-b5e4-fd60747833ab"}
